1
00:00:00,539 --> 00:00:01,859
Take a look at this.

2
00:00:01,859 --> 00:00:08,090
So you see this price action sequence, you
see this trendline, you wait for the breakout

3
00:00:08,090 --> 00:00:12,549
below it, and you enter when price closes
below it.

4
00:00:12,549 --> 00:00:19,240
And what do you know, price returns to the
trend line and continues in the initial direction.

5
00:00:19,240 --> 00:00:21,600
Sound familiar, right?

6
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:27,689
Trend lines are the simplest tools in technical
analysis, and maybe the hardest setup to trade.

7
00:00:27,689 --> 00:00:31,310
Much harder than a classic support or resistance
level.

8
00:00:31,310 --> 00:00:37,649
In this example, I see maybe 4 or 5 reasons
of why you shouldn’t have taken this trade

9
00:00:37,649 --> 00:00:39,300
in the first place.

10
00:00:39,300 --> 00:00:44,200
If you’re guilty of making the same mistake,
get ready to take some notes, because you're

11
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:51,289
about to discover the keys to mastering trendlines
and how to make the most of your trading strategies.

12
00:00:51,289 --> 00:00:55,170
Like, subscribe and stick around for the full
video.

13
00:00:55,170 --> 00:01:01,250
Don’t include prices that were not maintained
during a period

14
00:01:01,250 --> 00:01:07,810
Drawing trendlines without wicks is, in my
opinion, a better approach, because it eliminates

15
00:01:07,810 --> 00:01:09,080
noise.

16
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:14,360
A wick is the highest or lowest price that
was reached during the period represented

17
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:15,590
by that candlestick.

18
00:01:15,590 --> 00:01:17,780
A rejection of price.

19
00:01:17,780 --> 00:01:22,640
When you draw a trendline using the wicks
of the candlesticks, you are including prices

20
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:28,630
that were not maintained during that period,
and this can lead to more false signals, and

21
00:01:28,630 --> 00:01:31,280
a less accurate trend line.

22
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:37,140
For example, if you draw a trendline using
the wicks of a bullish candlestick, the trend

23
00:01:37,140 --> 00:01:42,300
line will be a bit lower than if you draw
it using the body of the candlestick.

24
00:01:42,300 --> 00:01:48,000
This difference may not seem significant,
but it can make a big difference in the outcome

25
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:49,770
of a trade.

26
00:01:49,770 --> 00:01:54,600
When you have a large wick on one side of
the candle, it could indicate that the price

27
00:01:54,600 --> 00:02:00,409
got rejected in that level, this could be
a sign of a potential reversal, but if you

28
00:02:00,409 --> 00:02:06,280
are drawing your trendline with the wicks,
you might be taking that large wick as a valid

29
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:09,509
price point, leading you to a false conclusion.

30
00:02:09,509 --> 00:02:14,250
So start drawing trend lines using only the
body of the candlesticks.

31
00:02:14,250 --> 00:02:20,370
A trendline connecting only 2 points is highly
unreliable

32
00:02:20,370 --> 00:02:26,790
A big mistake I’ve personally made for several
years, is to focus on trend lines that connect

33
00:02:26,790 --> 00:02:28,670
only 2 points.

34
00:02:28,670 --> 00:02:32,690
You see 2 swings and you connect them with
a trend line.

35
00:02:32,690 --> 00:02:38,930
I’ve lost far too many trades, chasing false
breakouts using this technique.

36
00:02:38,930 --> 00:02:43,790
When drawing trendlines, the more connecting
points, the better.

37
00:02:43,790 --> 00:02:49,480
This is because the more connecting points
a trendline has, the more reliable and robust

38
00:02:49,480 --> 00:02:51,260
it becomes.

39
00:02:51,260 --> 00:02:57,310
A trendline with more connecting points is
more reliable because it has been tested against

40
00:02:57,310 --> 00:03:04,010
more price swings and has been able to withstand
those tests, indicating that the trend has

41
00:03:04,010 --> 00:03:07,340
momentum and is likely to continue.

42
00:03:07,340 --> 00:03:13,319
If you have a trendline connecting two points,
it can be considered as a weak trendline,

43
00:03:13,319 --> 00:03:17,480
and let’s face it, it can be easily broken.

44
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:23,840
But if you have a trendline connecting 3 or
4 points, then you have a strong trendline.

45
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:29,439
When you see a clear breakout from a strong
trendline, it means something.

46
00:03:29,439 --> 00:03:34,970
The point is: when you are drawing a trendline
with only two points, you could be seeing

47
00:03:34,970 --> 00:03:40,720
a coincidence, but when you have a trendline
connecting more points, you can be sure that

48
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:46,800
the trend is real and it has been established
over a longer period of time.

49
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:55,180
Consider trend lines as noise zones
So price is constantly changing, impacted

50
00:03:55,180 --> 00:03:57,880
by volatility and momentum.

51
00:03:57,880 --> 00:04:02,379
This is particularly relevant when analyzing
trendlines.

52
00:04:02,379 --> 00:04:09,090
Professional traders are very aware that amateurs
are likely to place trades around trendlines

53
00:04:09,090 --> 00:04:15,900
and will often manipulate the market to cause
the price to spike, then change direction.

54
00:04:15,900 --> 00:04:21,919
To improve your win rate, it can be beneficial
to use areas rather than relying solely on

55
00:04:21,919 --> 00:04:24,449
single trend lines.

56
00:04:24,449 --> 00:04:30,850
For example, when using a single trendline,
you may be hesitant to enter a trade if the

57
00:04:30,850 --> 00:04:35,650
price is just slightly above or below this
trendline.

58
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:42,009
However, by using an area, you set a range
of prices where the price is likely to find

59
00:04:42,009 --> 00:04:44,050
support or resistance.

60
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:47,759
Here a quick tip on Tradingview.

61
00:04:47,759 --> 00:04:55,290
First you draw the trend line connecting the
swing lows, then you hold the CTRL key and

62
00:04:55,290 --> 00:04:59,550
drag the line to form the area.

63
00:04:59,550 --> 00:05:04,520
This can give you a bit more wiggle room to
enter or exit a trade.

64
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:10,600
By creating these so-called "noise zone",
you can filter out a significant amount of

65
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:18,990
market noise and eliminate the need to draw
trendlines precisely at the highs or lows.

66
00:05:18,990 --> 00:05:24,015
A shortening time between touches can indicate
a potential breakout

67
00:05:24,015 --> 00:05:28,080
The distance between connecting points is
crucial when determining the validity of your

68
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:29,410
trend line.

69
00:05:29,410 --> 00:05:36,520
When forming an up trendline, the swing lows
should not be too far apart or too close together,

70
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:40,830
as this can question the validity of a future
reaction.

71
00:05:40,830 --> 00:05:46,979
Similarly, when forming a down trend line,
the swing highs should also be relatively

72
00:05:46,979 --> 00:05:48,280
evenly spaced.

73
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:55,139
There isn’t an ideal distance between these
points, it will depend on the timeframe you’re

74
00:05:55,139 --> 00:05:56,139
analyzing.

75
00:05:56,139 --> 00:06:02,110
It is important to measure the time passed
between consecutive touches on a trendline.

76
00:06:02,110 --> 00:06:10,550
Here’s an important tip: a shortening time
between touches can indicate a potential breakout.

77
00:06:10,550 --> 00:06:17,099
When the market repeatedly tests a trend line
over a short period and the price stays close

78
00:06:17,099 --> 00:06:22,830
to the trendline, it is likely that a breakout
will occur, and the trend may be reversing.

79
00:06:22,830 --> 00:06:29,010
Though this is not always the case, this pattern
can indicate a good opportunity for trading

80
00:06:29,010 --> 00:06:35,160
a breakout, rather than a continuation play.

81
00:06:35,160 --> 00:06:39,990
As the angle of the trendline becomes steeper,
its reliability decreases

82
00:06:39,990 --> 00:06:45,259
The slope of a trendline can impact its validity
as a support or resistance level.

83
00:06:45,259 --> 00:06:51,090
Let's say we have a chart with price that
has been steadily increasing over time.

84
00:06:51,090 --> 00:06:56,509
As the price rises, you can draw a trendline
connecting the lows.

85
00:06:56,509 --> 00:07:01,830
This trendline will have a relatively shallow
angle, indicating that the price has been

86
00:07:01,830 --> 00:07:05,960
rising at a steady and consistent pace.

87
00:07:05,960 --> 00:07:11,520
This trendline can be considered a reliable
support level, as it is likely that the price

88
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:15,419
will continue to find support at this level.

89
00:07:15,419 --> 00:07:21,419
Now, let's say that the price suddenly experiences
a sharp and rapid increase.

90
00:07:21,419 --> 00:07:26,990
If we were to connect the lows during this
time, the trendline would have a much steeper

91
00:07:26,990 --> 00:07:27,990
angle.

92
00:07:27,990 --> 00:07:33,849
This sudden and sharp increase in price is
not likely to be sustained, and it is less

93
00:07:33,849 --> 00:07:37,729
likely that the price will continue to find
support at this level.

94
00:07:37,729 --> 00:07:39,562
This trendline would be considered less reliable
as a support level.

95
00:07:39,562 --> 00:07:45,020
So as the angle of the trendline becomes steeper,
the reliability of the level decreases.

96
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:51,960
In fact, a steep trendline is often the result
of a sudden and significant price movement

97
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:54,750
over a short period of time.

98
00:07:54,750 --> 00:08:00,960
Such trendlines created from sharp moves are
less likely to provide a meaningful support

99
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:02,319
or resistance level.

100
00:08:02,319 --> 00:08:08,440
Even if the trendline is constructed with
many valid points, attempting to profit from

101
00:08:08,440 --> 00:08:11,160
a trendline break may prove challenging.

102
00:08:11,160 --> 00:08:16,460
Continuation or breakout: which one you should
target

103
00:08:16,460 --> 00:08:21,669
There’s a special appeal to trade a trend
line breakout.

104
00:08:21,669 --> 00:08:26,960
I don’t know why, but many new traders prefer
to wait for the trendline to be breached,

105
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:29,039
then trade the potential breakout.

106
00:08:29,039 --> 00:08:35,310
I’ve also been guilty of this mistake, and
now I can tell you that trading in the direction

107
00:08:35,310 --> 00:08:41,140
of the trendline is a more consistent strategy
than trading breakouts.

108
00:08:41,140 --> 00:08:46,089
This allows you to ride the trend and take
advantage of the momentum that is already

109
00:08:46,089 --> 00:08:47,610
present in the market.

110
00:08:47,610 --> 00:08:54,780
For example, let's say that you have identified
an uptrend on a chart and you have drawn a

111
00:08:54,780 --> 00:08:57,690
trendline connecting the lows of the price.

112
00:08:57,690 --> 00:09:03,579
It’s better to trade in the direction of
this trendline, meaning you would be buying

113
00:09:03,579 --> 00:09:06,740
when the price is approaching the trendline.

114
00:09:06,740 --> 00:09:12,850
You want to capture the upward momentum of
the market and not wait for a breakout, which

115
00:09:12,850 --> 00:09:16,220
it may not be valid in the first place.

116
00:09:16,220 --> 00:09:21,180
Another advantage of trading in the direction
of the trendline is that it allows you to

117
00:09:21,180 --> 00:09:28,529
place stop losses below or above the trendline,
providing a clear level of risk management.

118
00:09:28,529 --> 00:09:32,730
Not to close though, because you don’t want
to be the victim of stop loss hunting.

119
00:09:32,730 --> 00:09:41,839
Wait for the first retest after breakout
Many traders are drawing a trendline, and

120
00:09:41,839 --> 00:09:46,380
at the first candle close below it, they enter
right away.

121
00:09:46,380 --> 00:09:54,170
But, the first retest after a trendline breakout
is a much better area to take trades from.

122
00:09:54,170 --> 00:09:55,570
So why is that?

123
00:09:55,570 --> 00:10:01,260
A big number of traders will place trades
in the direction of the trendline.

124
00:10:01,260 --> 00:10:07,150
When the market moved below it, then all of
the traders who have placed buy trades at

125
00:10:07,150 --> 00:10:11,380
the trend line are trapped in losing trades.

126
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:16,890
Their biggest desire, when the price is below
the trendline, is for market to return to

127
00:10:16,890 --> 00:10:18,100
their entry level.

128
00:10:18,100 --> 00:10:23,980
A lot of buyers will wait for a breakeven
chance, to close their positions.

129
00:10:23,980 --> 00:10:30,079
Different traders will decide to close their
trades at different times, and the closer

130
00:10:30,079 --> 00:10:35,510
the market gets to the breakout point the
higher the number of traders who will be closing

131
00:10:35,510 --> 00:10:36,640
their trades.

132
00:10:36,640 --> 00:10:42,430
That’s why you’ll see an immediate reaction
when the price returns to the trendline.

133
00:10:42,430 --> 00:10:46,600
The losing traders had their chance to exit
their trades.

134
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:53,700
Buyers are exiting, more sell orders are coming
into the market, and this adds momentum, to

135
00:10:53,700 --> 00:10:54,700
the downside.

136
00:10:54,700 --> 00:11:03,540
In some cases, when you wait for the first
retest, you’ll get a better price to enter.

137
00:11:03,540 --> 00:11:09,020
I personally trade only the first retest and
ignore the following tests.

138
00:11:09,020 --> 00:11:14,709
I have one rule: the breakout level can only
be touched once.

139
00:11:14,709 --> 00:11:20,680
When a level has been hit once, its significance
in the market decrease dramatically and the

140
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:26,130
chances of the market reacting to the level
in the same way again is low.

141
00:11:26,130 --> 00:11:33,010
If the market returns to the trend line breakout
area again after already being touched, the

142
00:11:33,010 --> 00:11:38,540
traders who went short on the breakout may
not be in their trades anymore.

143
00:11:38,540 --> 00:11:43,709
Traders will not sit and watch as the profit
on their trades gets smaller and smaller,

144
00:11:43,709 --> 00:11:49,630
they will always close their trades whilst
they still have a little bit of profit left.

145
00:11:49,630 --> 00:11:54,769
At the second or third retest, you could be
facing a lack of orders present in the market.

146
00:11:54,769 --> 00:11:58,529
So focus on the first re-test.

147
00:11:58,529 --> 00:12:04,620
Higher time frames trend lines are less likely
to be affected by short-term volatility

148
00:12:04,620 --> 00:12:09,260
Trend lines on higher time frames are considered
to be the most significant.

149
00:12:09,260 --> 00:12:15,120
For instance, a trend line that extends over
a two-week period will always be considered

150
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:20,889
more important than one that only extends
over the course of a trading session.

151
00:12:20,889 --> 00:12:25,110
To achieve the best results with trend lines,
it’s better to use higher time frames, it

152
00:12:25,110 --> 00:12:27,450
increases the reliability of the analysis.

153
00:12:27,450 --> 00:12:33,639
For example, let's say we're looking at a
chart and we've drawn a trend line on the

154
00:12:33,639 --> 00:12:35,520
daily chart.

155
00:12:35,520 --> 00:12:41,390
This line represents the overall direction
of the price over the past few weeks or even

156
00:12:41,390 --> 00:12:42,399
months.

157
00:12:42,399 --> 00:12:49,170
Now, if we switch to a lower time frame like
the 15-min chart, we may see that the price

158
00:12:49,170 --> 00:12:53,170
is also following an opposite trend line.

159
00:12:53,170 --> 00:12:58,320
But when you’re looking at the 15-min trend
line, you're only seeing the price action

160
00:12:58,320 --> 00:13:00,730
over the past several hours.

161
00:13:00,730 --> 00:13:07,139
The trend line on this chart is more likely
to be influenced by short-term factors.

162
00:13:07,139 --> 00:13:08,390
Which one has more relevance?

163
00:13:08,390 --> 00:13:11,440
Of course, is the higher time frame one.

164
00:13:11,440 --> 00:13:17,000
There is more data, more bars that are used
to make the trend line, this makes it more

165
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:23,860
reliable, and it's less likely to be affected
by short-term volatility.

166
00:13:23,860 --> 00:13:28,290
Confirm the trendline with VWAP or a moving
average

167
00:13:28,290 --> 00:13:33,730
One of the main things to remember when trading
trend lines is that using an approach that

168
00:13:33,730 --> 00:13:38,950
utilizes multiple confirmations is generally
the best way to go.

169
00:13:38,950 --> 00:13:43,320
The more confirmations, the less chance of
a false signal.

170
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:48,880
It's always helpful to look for confluences
in your chart, which is when multiple signals

171
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:51,430
point to the same conclusion.

172
00:13:51,430 --> 00:13:57,180
One example of this is when a trendline aligns
with a long term moving average.

173
00:13:57,180 --> 00:14:04,100
Let's say we're looking at a chart and we've
drawn a trendline on the hourly chart.

174
00:14:04,100 --> 00:14:09,580
This line represents the overall direction
of price over the past days.

175
00:14:09,580 --> 00:14:15,690
If we add a moving average to the chart, we
can see that the price is consistently bouncing

176
00:14:15,690 --> 00:14:20,949
off the moving average line, which also confirms
the trendline.

177
00:14:20,949 --> 00:14:26,610
Another example is when the price is consistently
trading above the moving average line and

178
00:14:26,610 --> 00:14:32,709
the trendline is also pointing upwards, it
gives you a better indication of the bullish

179
00:14:32,709 --> 00:14:33,720
trend.

180
00:14:33,720 --> 00:14:39,540
When a trendline aligns with a moving average,
it provides a level of added confidence in

181
00:14:39,540 --> 00:14:47,630
the trend direction, as it confirms the trendline
and can increase the reliability of your analysis.

182
00:14:47,630 --> 00:14:53,290
When these indicators give conflicting signals,
you have a warning sign, and it’s better

183
00:14:53,290 --> 00:14:58,000
to wait for further price action to unfold.

184
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:03,550
So like I said in the intro, trading trendlines
is much harder than trading classic support

185
00:15:03,550 --> 00:15:05,790
and resistance levels.

186
00:15:05,790 --> 00:15:11,529
If you want to have the full picture, you
definitely must watch this video.

187
00:15:11,529 --> 00:15:17,190
And check out our academy program, if you
want to further level up your trading.

188
00:15:17,190 --> 00:15:17,650
Until next time!

